<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-317-855  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 317 855.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  Feb 1989 v6 n2 p29(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Viruses and the susceptible society.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Serlin, Omri.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Society becomes more fragile as it becomes more reliant on easilydisrupted technology, and critical computer resources should beprotected more effectively before being interconnected.andO;Completely legitimate uses of computers can and do go wrong, butcomputer systems are also vulnerable to illicit penetration byhackers or abuses by insiders.andP;  Computer viruses, such as thatintroduced into ARPAnet in Nov 1988, can be especially disruptiveand costly.andP;  Unix is the most indulgent target for computerviruses due to wide availability of source code and widespreadinterconnection of Unix systems via electronic mail.andO;Additionally, Unix grew in an atmosphere that accepted andencouraged hacking, and considered 'secret back doors' in the codecute tricks.andP;  Meanwhile, in the benchmark wars, IBM has publishedDebitCredit benchmark test results for a 9377-90 configurationwhich differ greatly from results obtained by DEC on the samemachine.andP;  These performance and price discrepancies are especiallyembarrassing for DEC; they underscore the importance ofestablishing standard, unambiguous performance standards, and ofaccompanying performance claims with 'full disclosure'documentation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM; DEC.andO;Topic:     Computer HackersComputer VirusesUNIXSecurityComputer SystemsPerformance Measurement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>